Germany Daybook: ECB Members Signal Further Policy Tightening

-- B y   A l l i s o n   C o n n o l l y
-- 
2011-04-18T06:24:48Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-18/germany-daybook-ecb-members-signal-further-policy-tightening.html
European Central Bank  Governing
Council members signaled they will keep tightening monetary
policy this year as their economy strengthens and inflation
accelerates at its fastest pace since 2008.  Investor expectations of an increase in the benchmark
 interest rate  by another 50 basis points in 2011 are “well-founded,” Austria’s Ewald Nowotny told  Bloomberg News  in
Washington on April 16. Luc Coene of Belgium said in an
interview yesterday that monetary “conditions are too
accommodative.”  EQUITIES:
*Deutsche Telekom (DTE GR) and  France Telecom  (FTE FP) agreed to
combine their procurement businesses in a joint venture that
will save the companies a combined EU1.3B.
*Deutsche Bank (DBK GR) and LGT have ended talks on the sale of
BHF-Bank AG, the German lender said in a statement today.
*RWE (RWE GR) may benefit from the shutdown of its Biblis
nuclear power plant in the medium-term because electricity
prices could rise with less supply on the market,  Der Spiegel 
reported.
*Siemens (SIE GR) is “very bullish” on the U.S. even with the
current economic environment, Chief Executive  Peter Loescher 
said in an interview with the Washington Post.
*A top ThyssenKrupp (TKA GR) executive was convicted of murder
in Italy for a fire at a steel plant there in 2007, which killed
seven workers.
*Air Berlin’s (AB1 GR) first-quarter results were hurt by the
unrest in North Africa, Chief Financial Officer Ulf Huettmeyer
said in an interview with  Der Tagesspiegel .
*BMW (BMW GR) suspended sales to Argentina after it failed to
reach an accord with the government to shrink the company’s
trade deficit in the country, newspaper Clarin said.
*VW (VOW GR) may increase its China workforce to many as 85,000
by 2015 from the current 50,000, Karl-Thomas Neumann, chief
executive officer of Volkswagen Group China, said in Shanghai
today.
*Continental AG (CON GR) signed an agreement to acquire Modi
Tyres, a unit of India’s Modi Rubber (MDR IN). Continental gave
no details on the terms of the deal.
*Phoenix Solar (PS4 GR) expects sales in 2011 to be unchanged or
“marginally” higher than last year, sees “stronger” growth in
revenue and ebit in 2012.  ECONOMY:
*European Central Bank governing council member  Yves Mersch  said
“the growth dynamics is carrying on and is firming” in the euro
region.
*German Finance Minister  Wolfgang Schaeuble  said policy makers
from the Group of 20 nations are making ‘gradual’ progress
toward a framework that aims to curb excessive capital flows.
*Greece said it has no plans for a debt restructuring even as
German officials openly discuss the possibility and investors
charge a record amount to insure the country’s obligations.
*German  tax revenue  could climb EU10B higher next year compared
with the last estimate and as much as EU8B more in 2011,
Handelsblatt said, citing an estimate from the Halle-based IWH
institute.  GOVERNMENT:
*The German government froze $6 billion of Libyan state funds
over the last few weeks, Der Spiegel reported, citing a memo
written by Economy Minister  Rainer Bruederle .
*The German state of North Rhine-Westphalia wants to pursue its
own “nuclear-free”  energy policy , Harry Voigtsberger, the
state’s finance minister, said in an interview with
Handelsblatt.
*German Health Minister Philipp Roesler, who’s running to become
leader of the Free Democratic Party, said his party opposes
raising taxes to pay for alternative energy to replace nuclear
power, the Passauer Neue Presse quoted him as saying.  MARKETS:
*The DAX Index gained 0.4% to 7,178.29.
*The Stoxx Europe 600 Index fell 0.3% to 277.78.
*MSCI Asia-Pacific Index lost 0.2% to 135,61 as of 8:21
Frankfurt time.
*German 10-year bond yield at 3.38%.
*Euro -- U.S. $1.437.  To contact the reporters on this story:
